    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and it's super frustrating. i've been making my payments on time every month, but it feels like the actual principal amount barely moves. can you explain how the interest calculation works on a declining balance so i can understand why the balance isn't dropping faster?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The interest calculation on a declining balance loan is a bit like a slow, steady drip that eventually lets the dam break. You are being charged interest on the remaining principal balance each month, which is why it feels like you're just chipping away at the debt. As you pay, the principal goes down, which in turn lowers the amount of interest charged in the *next* month. This is why the early payments go mostly toward interest, and the later payments start tackling the principal faster.",
      "source": "target",
