      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Imagine you have a loan balance of $\\$10,000$ with a $5\\%$ annual interest rate, and you make a $\\$200$ payment. First, you calculate the monthly interest: $(\\$10,000 \\times 0.05) / 12$ equals $\\$41.67$. Then, the remainder of your payment, $\\$200 - \\$41.67 = \\$158.33$, goes directly to reducing the principal. This process repeats, but because the principal is now $\\$9,841.67$, the next month's interest charge will be slightly less, which is how the balance slowly shrinks.",
      "source": "target",
